530
00:28:23,140 --> 00:28:24,840
You know, um,

531
00:28:24,870 --> 00:28:27,500
a very intuitive lady
once said to me...

532
00:28:27,540 --> 00:28:30,340
"I believe these things happen
to me for a reason,

533
00:28:30,370 --> 00:28:32,100
"and the challenge is having
the patience

534
00:28:32,140 --> 00:28:34,500
to wait for the reason
to reveal itself."

535
00:28:34,540 --> 00:28:36,000
Oh, zip it.

536
00:28:36,040 --> 00:28:38,800
Anyway, I called Mrs.
Pasternack down the street.

537
00:28:38,840 --> 00:28:41,500
She's going to take the girls
home with her.

538
00:28:41,540 --> 00:28:44,100
So if you could stop by
her place on the way home...

539
00:28:44,140 --> 00:28:46,770
Thy will be done.

540
00:28:51,270 --> 00:28:53,100
CRIME TECH:
Everything we can do
here, we've done.

541
00:28:53,140 --> 00:28:54,240
The rest of it

542
00:28:54,270 --> 00:28:55,940
really ought to happen
back at the lab.

543
00:28:55,970 --> 00:28:58,000
I made a call-- flatbed's
on its way out here.

544
00:28:58,040 --> 00:28:59,700
Anything you want to share?

545
00:28:59,740 --> 00:29:00,900
Well, wherever
they were going,

546
00:29:00,940 --> 00:29:03,500
they knew it was going to
take them a while to get there.

547
00:29:03,540 --> 00:29:05,940
Car's full of clothes,
toiletries...

548
00:29:05,970 --> 00:29:07,070
No maps, though.

549
00:29:07,100 --> 00:29:09,070
No tickets or brochures.

550
00:29:09,100 --> 00:29:10,170
You get the feeling that maybe

551
00:29:10,200 --> 00:29:11,440
it was
a pretty spontaneous trip.

552
00:29:11,470 --> 00:29:13,500
But you got a lot of
the kinds of things

553
00:29:13,540 --> 00:29:17,100
you see on a long road trip,
like DVDs for the kid,

554
00:29:17,140 --> 00:29:19,370
fast food wrappers,
juice boxes...

555
00:29:19,400 --> 00:29:21,340
What's this?
It was in the player.

556
00:29:21,370 --> 00:29:22,970
They must've had it on

557
00:29:23,000 --> 00:29:24,740
when they went over the side--
The MonkeyHeads.

558
00:29:24,770 --> 00:29:27,000
Did you say Monkeyheads?

559
00:29:27,040 --> 00:29:28,300
Mm-hmm.

560
00:29:28,340 --> 00:29:30,200
SCANLON:
What's the big deal?

561
00:29:30,240 --> 00:29:31,500
Does that mean something?

562
00:29:31,540 --> 00:29:32,510
(gasping):
Oh, boy...

563
00:29:33,960 --> 00:29:35,510
1

564
00:29:42,020 --> 00:29:43,250
Hey, I'm home.

565
00:29:43,250 --> 00:29:45,850
Shh, shh, shh.
You'll wake the baby.

566
00:29:45,890 --> 00:29:47,340
Marie's already down?

567
00:29:47,340 --> 00:29:48,570
Have you looked
at your watch?

568
00:29:48,600 --> 00:29:50,240
It's after 9:00.

569
00:29:50,270 --> 00:29:52,770
Wow.
You do good work.

570
00:29:52,800 --> 00:29:54,070
What about Bridgette?

571
00:29:54,100 --> 00:29:55,570
I really need to
talk to Bridgette.

572
00:29:55,600 --> 00:29:56,700
Well, I don't know,

573
00:29:56,740 --> 00:29:58,340
she's been in bed
for half an hour,

574
00:29:58,370 --> 00:30:00,440
but I couldn't tell you
if she's asleep or not,

575
00:30:00,470 --> 00:30:02,340
'cause she fought me
every step of the way.

576
00:30:02,370 --> 00:30:04,400
Three days ago, she couldn't
wait to get to bed,

577
00:30:04,440 --> 00:30:05,470
and now she acts like

578
00:30:05,500 --> 00:30:07,100
I'm sending her off
to the electric chair.

579
00:30:07,140 --> 00:30:08,500
You going to have
some food?

580
00:30:08,540 --> 00:30:10,400
Later.
(sighs)

581
00:30:11,440 --> 00:30:13,400
Did you feel that?

582
00:30:13,440 --> 00:30:14,540
What?

583
00:30:14,570 --> 00:30:15,940
That blast of cold air?

584
00:30:15,970 --> 00:30:19,100
What are you talking about?

585
00:30:19,140 --> 00:30:22,240
I don't even think
the air-conditioning's on.

586
00:30:22,270 --> 00:30:22,440
I don't know.

587
00:30:22,440 --> 00:30:23,870
I've been
feeling them all night.

588
00:30:24,900 --> 00:30:26,600
Maybe it's just my imagination.

589
00:30:26,640 --> 00:30:29,770
Maybe you're going through
the change of life.

590
00:30:29,800 --> 00:30:31,300
Ah, could be.

591
00:30:38,000 --> 00:30:40,270
(whispering):
Bridgette.

592
00:30:40,300 --> 00:30:41,900
Bridgette?

593
00:30:43,970 --> 00:30:45,970
Hey. Hey.

594
00:30:46,000 --> 00:30:47,870
(gently):
Hey...

595
00:30:47,900 --> 00:30:49,470
What are you doing
with this?

596
00:30:49,500 --> 00:30:51,000
This is your sister's.

597
00:30:51,040 --> 00:30:52,640
Well, I wasn't hurting it.

598
00:30:52,670 --> 00:30:54,500
I was just listening to it.

599
00:30:54,540 --> 00:30:56,370
Well, you're not supposed
to be listening to it,

600
00:30:56,400 --> 00:30:58,270
you're supposed
to be asleep.

601
00:30:58,300 --> 00:31:00,100
Well, I don't want to be asleep.

602
00:31:00,140 --> 00:31:01,840
Sleeping is scary.

603
00:31:01,870 --> 00:31:04,100
I seeMonkeyheads
when I sleep.

604
00:31:04,140 --> 00:31:06,940
And why is that scary?

605
00:31:06,970 --> 00:31:09,040
Monkeyheads aren't scary.
Monkeyheads are funny.

606
00:31:09,070 --> 00:31:11,140
No, no, they're not.
Not lately.

607
00:31:11,170 --> 00:31:13,370
Really?

608
00:31:15,000 --> 00:31:17,140
Tell me what you've seen.

609
00:31:17,170 --> 00:31:19,640
Well, the other night,

610
00:31:19,670 --> 00:31:22,340
this mama monkey
and this baby monkey,

611
00:31:22,370 --> 00:31:23,470
they were in their car,

612
00:31:23,500 --> 00:31:25,870
and then these bad monkeys
chased them

613
00:31:25,900 --> 00:31:27,700
and chased them

614
00:31:27,740 --> 00:31:30,870
and then pushed them right off
the road and into this lake.

615
00:31:30,900 --> 00:31:32,640
And then?

616
00:31:32,670 --> 00:31:34,240
And then they just sat there,

617
00:31:34,270 --> 00:31:37,000
and they were upside-down,
and they were bleeding,

618
00:31:37,040 --> 00:31:39,240
and the car got filled
up all with water.

619
00:31:39,270 --> 00:31:40,800
And they just sat there.

620
00:31:40,840 --> 00:31:43,540
And then they were breathing
funny little cartoon bubbles.

621
00:31:43,570 --> 00:31:46,740
And then they
finally fell asleep,

622
00:31:46,770 --> 00:31:48,970
and turned into Angel Monkeys,

623
00:31:49,000 --> 00:31:51,840
and floated out the car
and up to heaven.

624
00:31:55,570 --> 00:31:57,540
Sweetie...

625
00:31:57,570 --> 00:32:00,440
Well, I can see why
you wouldn't want to have

626
00:32:00,470 --> 00:32:03,140
another dream like that.

627
00:32:03,170 --> 00:32:05,400
But here's
the thing, Bridge--

628
00:32:05,440 --> 00:32:09,140
I am almost 100% sure

629
00:32:09,170 --> 00:32:11,970
that the bad dreams are over.

630
00:32:12,000 --> 00:32:15,340
I really think it's okay
to go back to sleep.

631
00:32:15,370 --> 00:32:17,440
You do?
I do.

632
00:32:17,470 --> 00:32:19,700
And if, for some strange reason,
I'm wrong,

633
00:32:19,740 --> 00:32:21,840
you can come into my bed.

634
00:32:21,870 --> 00:32:25,840
But... I don't think I'm wrong.

635
00:32:25,870 --> 00:32:27,770
I think the bad dream
is over.

636
00:32:27,800 --> 00:32:29,470
Well, I hope so.

637
00:32:29,500 --> 00:32:31,970
'Cause it's really tiring
trying not to sleep.

638
00:32:34,440 --> 00:32:35,640
She dreamt it, too.

639
00:32:35,670 --> 00:32:37,200
The little boy,
the drowning.

640
00:32:37,240 --> 00:32:38,740
What are you
talking about?

641
00:32:38,770 --> 00:32:41,100
She dreamt a cartoon version
of the same thing I did.

642
00:32:41,140 --> 00:32:42,970
Cartoon?

643
00:32:43,000 --> 00:32:44,940
Why a cartoon?

644
00:32:44,970 --> 00:32:46,440
The little boy

645
00:32:46,470 --> 00:32:48,300
was watching cartoons
when he drowned.

646
00:32:48,340 --> 00:32:51,240
I suppose he was trying to make
peace with the way he died,

647
00:32:51,270 --> 00:32:54,100
trying to find someone
to tell his story to.

648
00:32:54,140 --> 00:32:57,040
They're about
the same age.

649
00:32:57,070 --> 00:32:59,470
I hate that she dreams
that stuff.

650
00:32:59,500 --> 00:33:00,900
I know.

651
00:33:00,940 --> 00:33:04,270
For what it's worth,
I think she's okay.

652
00:33:04,300 --> 00:33:06,570
She really thinks
it is a cartoon.

653
00:33:06,600 --> 00:33:09,740
A scary cartoon,
but still a cartoon.

654
00:33:09,770 --> 00:33:11,470
And I do think it's over.

655
00:33:11,500 --> 00:33:13,770
Oh...

656
00:33:13,800 --> 00:33:15,270
God.

657
00:33:15,300 --> 00:33:16,940
Tell me you don't feel that.

658
00:33:16,970 --> 00:33:18,570
Feel what?

659
00:33:18,600 --> 00:33:19,940
It's like arctic.

660
00:33:19,970 --> 00:33:23,070
You didn't feel
that cold blast of air?

661
00:33:23,100 --> 00:33:27,040
Come here, let me
feel your head.

662
00:33:32,500 --> 00:33:34,540
You don't feel feverish.

663
00:33:34,570 --> 00:33:36,100
But why don't you go
lay down in bed?

664
00:33:36,140 --> 00:33:37,540
I'll be in in a minute.

665
00:33:37,570 --> 00:33:38,740
I don't feel sick.

666
00:33:38,770 --> 00:33:40,570
I don't know what to tell you.

667
00:33:40,600 --> 00:33:42,170
It's Phoenix, Arizona.

668
00:33:42,200 --> 00:33:44,740
If you're feeling the chills,
you're getting sick.

669
00:33:44,770 --> 00:33:46,070
Just go.

670
00:33:46,100 --> 00:33:48,940
I'll clean up.
I'll lock up.

671
00:34:07,400 --> 00:34:09,840
Hey, Al.

672
00:34:09,870 --> 00:34:12,500
Sorry about the cold.

673
00:34:12,540 --> 00:34:15,440
I hear it goes away,
eventually, though.

674
00:34:16,800 --> 00:34:18,600
What else have you heard?

675
00:34:18,640 --> 00:34:22,040
Oh... that you can see me.

676
00:34:22,070 --> 00:34:24,300
That you can hear me.

677
00:34:24,340 --> 00:34:28,100
That, uh, that's pretty rare.

678
00:34:29,440 --> 00:34:32,470
I am really sorry, Clay.

679
00:34:32,470 --> 00:34:35,120
The other day,
outside my house...

680
00:34:35,120 --> 00:34:36,230
I wasn't sure.

681
00:34:36,240 --> 00:34:38,540
I thought you might be...

682
00:34:38,570 --> 00:34:40,300
But I wasn't sure.

683
00:34:42,340 --> 00:34:45,200
I'm really glad you're here.

684
00:34:45,240 --> 00:34:48,800
I'm really glad
I get to say good-bye.

685
00:34:48,840 --> 00:34:50,600
Don't be sorry.
Nothing to be sorry about.

686
00:34:50,640 --> 00:34:53,970
Truth is, I've been flirting
with this all my life.

687
00:34:54,000 --> 00:34:56,540
Now that I'm here...

688
00:34:56,570 --> 00:35:00,170
it's not like the view's
all that bad.

689
00:35:02,440 --> 00:35:04,640
You know what
else I heard?

690
00:35:04,670 --> 00:35:06,400
What's that?

691
00:35:06,440 --> 00:35:09,700
That if I try hard enough,

692
00:35:09,740 --> 00:35:14,070
that if I want it bad enough,

693
00:35:14,100 --> 00:35:17,840
sometimes, someone like me

694
00:35:17,870 --> 00:35:21,740
can be felt...

695
00:35:21,770 --> 00:35:24,070
by someone like you.

696
00:35:24,100 --> 00:35:26,070
I have to tell you,
I've never...

697
00:35:26,100 --> 00:35:28,200
Allison?

698
00:35:28,240 --> 00:35:29,940
Do you want a hand
locking up?

699
00:35:32,240 --> 00:35:34,500
Uh... sure.

700
00:35:34,540 --> 00:35:37,500
Absolutely.

701
00:35:48,470 --> 00:35:50,140
Hello, Detective.

702
00:35:50,170 --> 00:35:51,390
Your deputy-ship.

703
00:35:51,390 --> 00:35:52,990
Haven't seen you
in a couple of days.

704
00:35:53,020 --> 00:35:54,390
You know what's been going on.

705
00:35:54,420 --> 00:35:56,520
I look up from my desk,
it's 11:00 at night.

706
00:35:56,550 --> 00:35:57,850
Well, the mayor's
back in town now.

707
00:35:57,890 --> 00:35:59,620
I saw it right on the
front page of the paper.

708
00:35:59,650 --> 00:36:01,650
No reason for you not
to come over tonight.

709
00:36:01,690 --> 00:36:03,450
Well, then maybe I will.

710
00:36:03,490 --> 00:36:05,650
Well, if you ring the bell,
maybe I'll let you in.

711
00:36:05,690 --> 00:36:06,950
10:00-ish okay?

712
00:36:06,990 --> 00:36:08,630
I got a call from this woman
in the third district.

713
00:36:08,640 --> 00:36:10,040
Worked on our last campaign.

714
00:36:10,070 --> 00:36:11,240
Wants to buy me a drink.

715
00:36:11,270 --> 00:36:12,340
She was very insistent.

716
00:36:12,370 --> 00:36:14,440
You sure it was a woman?

717
00:36:15,820 --> 00:36:17,200
Don't you have somewhere
you need to be?

718
00:36:17,200 --> 00:36:18,440
Oh, um...

719
00:36:18,470 --> 00:36:22,440
So... 10:00-ish.

720
00:36:28,840 --> 00:36:30,840
Hey.

721
00:36:30,870 --> 00:36:32,800
Hey.

722
00:36:32,840 --> 00:36:35,100
(clears throat)
Allison here yet?

723
00:36:35,140 --> 00:36:37,340
She's the one who wanted
to have this meeting.

724
00:36:37,370 --> 00:36:40,070
I've got a doctor's thing
this afternoon,

725
00:36:40,100 --> 00:36:41,500
desk full of work.

726
00:36:41,540 --> 00:36:44,200
Excuse me.

727
00:36:46,040 --> 00:36:48,140
SCANLON:
The dead woman, the
driver of the minivan,

728
00:36:48,170 --> 00:36:50,000
name is Olga Bankova.

729
00:36:50,040 --> 00:36:51,500
She's a naturalized
U.S. citizen,

730
00:36:51,540 --> 00:36:54,100
34 years old, single mother,
artist of some kind.

731
00:36:54,140 --> 00:36:55,870
Also works as a substitute
teacher; no priors.

732
00:36:55,900 --> 00:36:58,540
They were over 200 miles
from home when they died.

733
00:36:58,570 --> 00:37:01,070
The child in the backseat
was her son Ian.

734
00:37:01,100 --> 00:37:02,070
Seven years old.

735
00:37:02,100 --> 00:37:04,300
What else do we know?
Not much.

736
00:37:04,340 --> 00:37:06,200
We're checking paint and body
shops around the state,

737
00:37:06,240 --> 00:37:08,500
looking for any large vehicles
with horizontal abrasions

738
00:37:08,540 --> 00:37:09,800
consistent with
the minivan's.

739
00:37:09,840 --> 00:37:12,300
So...

740
00:37:12,340 --> 00:37:14,840
we're certain the car
was pushed into that lake bed?

741
00:37:14,870 --> 00:37:17,370
No.
Yes.

742
00:37:17,400 --> 00:37:19,400
No one in the crime lab
is willing to say

743
00:37:19,440 --> 00:37:21,240
in a definitive way that the
minivan was actually pushed

744
00:37:21,270 --> 00:37:22,130
into that lake bed.

745
00:37:22,140 --> 00:37:24,550
Yes, there's paint on the car,
yes, the side is scraped

746
00:37:24,550 --> 00:37:25,790
consistent with that kind
of scenario

747
00:37:25,820 --> 00:37:27,350
but the vehicle also took
about a 40-foot fall,

748
00:37:27,390 --> 00:37:28,750
which could account
for the damage

749
00:37:28,790 --> 00:37:31,050
and the mismatched paint could
also be from a previous mishap.

750
00:37:31,090 --> 00:37:32,390
That coupled with the fact
that no one

751
00:37:32,420 --> 00:37:34,220
can seem to come up
with any kind of motive...

752
00:37:34,250 --> 00:37:36,150
I know that she was pushed
off the road.

753
00:37:36,190 --> 00:37:37,990
I saw it happen.
My daughter saw it, too.

754
00:37:38,020 --> 00:37:40,050
Your daughter?

755
00:37:40,090 --> 00:37:41,350
Really?

756
00:37:41,390 --> 00:37:42,590
Did either one of you,
perchance,

757
00:37:42,620 --> 00:37:44,090
see who was driving
the other vehicle?

758
00:37:44,120 --> 00:37:47,050
I didn't, no.

759
00:37:48,840 --> 00:37:49,780
What about your daughter?

760
00:37:49,790 --> 00:37:52,620
My daughter doesn't have any
information you could use.

761
00:37:52,650 --> 00:37:53,890
I don't understand.

762
00:37:53,920 --> 00:37:56,220
I'm gathering that, like you,

763
00:37:56,250 --> 00:37:57,990
your daughter saw all this
in a dream.

764
00:37:58,020 --> 00:38:00,490
Don't you think
it might be useful to us

765
00:38:00,520 --> 00:38:02,750
to interview her, see
if we couldn't piece together

766
00:38:02,790 --> 00:38:04,250
some kind of description?

767
00:38:04,290 --> 00:38:06,750
I'm familiar with a number of
people from around the state

768
00:38:06,790 --> 00:38:08,250
who have a lot of expertise

769
00:38:08,290 --> 00:38:09,750
when it comes
to interviewing children.

770
00:38:09,790 --> 00:38:12,590
I mean, we'd have to finesse
the whole dream thing,

771
00:38:12,620 --> 00:38:14,750
but I'm sure
it could be handled.

772
00:38:16,790 --> 00:38:20,950
She saw them,
but she didn't see them.

773
00:38:21,850 --> 00:38:23,520
Look, it was a cartoon.

774
00:38:23,550 --> 00:38:25,150
She saw the whole thing
as a cartoon.

775
00:38:25,190 --> 00:38:29,020
The people who pushed
the minivan off the road

776
00:38:29,050 --> 00:38:31,190
were cartoon people.

777
00:38:31,220 --> 00:38:35,050
Everybody was a cartoon.

778
00:38:37,120 --> 00:38:40,220
I see.

779
00:38:41,000 --> 00:38:42,700
Any news
on the home invasion front?

780
00:38:42,740 --> 00:38:44,200
SCANLON:
Not really. No.

781
00:38:44,240 --> 00:38:46,200
Place turned out to be
amazingly clean.

782
00:38:46,240 --> 00:38:47,800
I mean,
clearly these guys were pros.

783
00:38:47,840 --> 00:38:50,370
Aha.

784
00:38:50,400 --> 00:38:52,720
No leads
on the home invasion front.

785
00:38:52,720 --> 00:38:54,350
Dark cartoon forces at work,

786
00:38:54,390 --> 00:38:56,050
pushing vehicles off
our thoroughfares.

787
00:38:56,090 --> 00:38:57,950
It's a wonderful day
to be the district attorney.

788
00:38:57,990 --> 00:38:59,820
Excuse me?

789
00:38:59,850 --> 00:39:01,520
You're excused.

790
00:39:03,320 --> 00:39:06,190
(mimics):
"It's a wonderful day
to be the district attorney."

791
00:39:06,190 --> 00:39:07,680
You know the man's under
a lot of pressure.

792
00:39:07,690 --> 00:39:09,720
That's not the point.
It was mean.

793
00:39:09,720 --> 00:39:10,850
It was needlessly mean.

794
00:39:10,890 --> 00:39:12,050
He's not himself.

795
00:39:12,090 --> 00:39:13,490
I don't know what's
wrong with him.

796
00:39:13,520 --> 00:39:15,350
Who are you guys talking about?
Nobody.

797
00:39:15,390 --> 00:39:17,190
You know, all they're talking
about on the radio is

798
00:39:17,220 --> 00:39:18,520
how these guys are
still out there,

799
00:39:18,550 --> 00:39:20,620
it's just a matter of time
before they do it again.

800
00:39:20,650 --> 00:39:21,990
Okay, I get it.

801
00:39:22,020 --> 00:39:24,390
He's under a lot of pressure
on that case,

802
00:39:24,420 --> 00:39:25,990
and I'm not helping him
on that case.

803
00:39:26,020 --> 00:39:27,150
Well, I'm sorry.

804
00:39:27,190 --> 00:39:28,790
I wish I could pick and choose
what I dream

805
00:39:28,820 --> 00:39:30,320
on any given day, but I can't.

806
00:39:30,350 --> 00:39:31,690
So it isn't
the crime du jour.

807
00:39:31,720 --> 00:39:33,190
I can't help that.

808
00:39:33,220 --> 00:39:35,750
I see what I see, and I know
what I know and my daughter...

809
00:39:35,790 --> 00:39:37,090
Uh-uh...
I think you're blowing this

810
00:39:37,120 --> 00:39:38,950
way out of proportion.
My daughter

811
00:39:38,990 --> 00:39:40,790
doesn't get to specify
the style of presentation

812
00:39:40,820 --> 00:39:43,920
when someone reaches out to her
from the great beyond

813
00:39:43,950 --> 00:39:46,090
to tell her something.
"Well, I'm sorry,

814
00:39:46,120 --> 00:39:47,950
we're not accepting
cartoon dreams today."

815
00:39:47,990 --> 00:39:50,890
The district attorney prefers
his clues from the other side

816
00:39:50,920 --> 00:39:52,520
more straightforward.

817
00:39:52,550 --> 00:39:53,890
More crime, less character.

818
00:39:53,920 --> 00:39:55,850
More like an episode
of Law & Order.

819
00:39:55,890 --> 00:39:56,850
Allison.

820
00:39:56,890 --> 00:39:58,450
Are you talking about me?

821
00:39:58,490 --> 00:40:00,050
No, honey,
nobody's talking about you.

822
00:40:00,090 --> 00:40:01,850
Nobody's talking about anybody.

823
00:40:01,890 --> 00:40:04,290
I need a bath.

824
00:40:05,750 --> 00:40:07,150
Is something wrong, Mommy?

825
00:40:07,190 --> 00:40:08,450
It's not you guys.

826
00:40:08,490 --> 00:40:10,420
Mommy just had a hard day.

827
00:40:11,490 --> 00:40:14,550
No, I'm, uh, I'm still here.

828
00:40:14,590 --> 00:40:16,420
Of course.
I know it's dinnertime.

829
00:40:16,450 --> 00:40:17,750
He just wanted
to run some tests,

830
00:40:17,790 --> 00:40:20,690
and I'm just sitting here
waiting for the results.

831
00:40:22,390 --> 00:40:24,050
I'll call you when I'm done.

832
00:40:24,090 --> 00:40:25,720
I love you, too.

833
00:40:37,520 --> 00:40:39,520
I've been guarding
it with my life.

834
00:40:39,550 --> 00:40:42,190
I appreciate it.

835
00:40:47,920 --> 00:40:49,720
Yeah?

836
00:40:50,750 --> 00:40:52,220
Bridge and Marie are down.

837
00:40:52,250 --> 00:40:54,250
Ariel's taking a shower.

838
00:40:54,290 --> 00:40:56,890
I thought I would just lock up
and go to bed.

839
00:40:56,920 --> 00:40:58,950
Oh, my God,
how long have I been in here?

840
00:40:58,990 --> 00:41:00,150
That's all right;
you look comfortable.

841
00:41:00,190 --> 00:41:01,420
You're allowed.

842
00:41:01,450 --> 00:41:03,720
I'll be back.
I won't let you drown.

843
00:41:19,020 --> 00:41:20,550
WOMAN:
We're very aware
of everything

844
00:41:20,590 --> 00:41:22,120
that's been going on
with the mayor.

845
00:41:22,150 --> 00:41:25,590
We're all aware
of how mercurial he can be.

846
00:41:25,620 --> 00:41:27,650
You've been very deft

847
00:41:27,690 --> 00:41:29,250
the way you've covered for him.

848
00:41:29,290 --> 00:41:30,890
That's my job.

849
00:41:30,920 --> 00:41:32,050
Oh, and you
do it well.

850
00:41:32,090 --> 00:41:36,420
You seem very, um,
at ease on television.

851
00:41:36,450 --> 00:41:37,580
Oh?

852
00:41:37,590 --> 00:41:39,880
Have you ever considered
running for office?

853
00:41:39,890 --> 00:41:41,350
Excuse me?

854
00:41:41,350 --> 00:41:44,720
We'd like to see you go after
a spot on city council.

855
00:42:06,420 --> 00:42:07,990
Oh, let me ask
you something.

856
00:42:08,020 --> 00:42:09,620
How do I do this?

857
00:42:09,650 --> 00:42:10,790
Just ask her.

858
00:42:10,820 --> 00:42:11,890
You got a boyfriend?

859
00:42:11,920 --> 00:42:13,850
Hopefully, a doctor
or a lawyer.

860
00:42:13,890 --> 00:42:15,790
Someone with some standing.

861
00:42:18,090 --> 00:42:19,850
I'm just kidding.

862
00:42:21,520 --> 00:42:23,850
But seriously, is there someone
we should know about?

863
00:42:23,890 --> 00:42:27,250
Whoever they are,
they're going to end up
being very involved.

864
00:42:27,250 --> 00:42:28,320
Please, whomever it might be,

865
00:42:28,350 --> 00:42:30,050
just don't let it be
a civil servant.

866
00:42:30,090 --> 00:42:32,220
All of the union agreements
are coming up in January,

867
00:42:32,250 --> 00:42:33,650
(laughs):
and that's all we need.

868
00:42:44,720 --> 00:42:46,120
I'd do that for you,
if I could.

869
00:42:47,310 --> 00:42:49,410
1

870
00:42:50,450 --> 00:42:52,230
I'm beginning to think
it's a big lie.

871
00:42:52,870 --> 00:42:53,470
2

872
00:42:53,480 --> 00:42:56,100
What are you doing here?
3

873
00:42:56,880 --> 00:42:57,850
4

874
00:42:57,850 --> 00:42:59,050
But that's crazy.

875
00:42:59,680 --> 00:43:02,110
That's wrong.
You can't be here.

876
00:43:02,150 --> 00:43:03,830
You can't do this.

877
00:43:03,830 --> 00:43:05,900
I have a family,
and you have someplace

878
00:43:05,930 --> 00:43:07,060
you're supposed to be.

879
00:43:07,100 --> 00:43:08,760
Well, I like it here.

880
00:43:08,800 --> 00:43:10,560
I like your house;
it feels good.

881
00:43:10,600 --> 00:43:11,700
I like your kids.

882
00:43:11,730 --> 00:43:14,060
You're not thinking clearly.

883
00:43:14,100 --> 00:43:16,060
You must still be in shock.

884
00:43:16,100 --> 00:43:17,600
And you're leaving
out my husband.

885
00:43:17,630 --> 00:43:19,100
I have a husband.
I have a life.

886
00:43:19,130 --> 00:43:20,760
Really?
(door opens)

887
00:43:20,800 --> 00:43:22,200
Locked and loaded.

888
00:43:27,100 --> 00:43:28,900
Hey, you know what?

889
00:43:28,930 --> 00:43:31,730
Wet becomes you, my darling.

890
00:43:31,760 --> 00:43:33,200
You look good like that.

891
00:43:34,460 --> 00:43:36,360
I may toss you
in that tub every night.

892
00:43:37,430 --> 00:43:39,060
"Wet becomes you"?

893
00:43:40,860 --> 00:43:43,160
This is so unfair.

894
00:43:43,200 --> 00:43:46,260
(chuckles)
What's that?
I say the wrong thing?

895
00:43:46,300 --> 00:43:47,760
You want me to go?

896
00:43:47,800 --> 00:43:49,460
Just say, "Clay,
I need you to go."

897
00:43:49,500 --> 00:43:51,630
JOE:
I can't help it.
You come over here

898
00:43:51,660 --> 00:43:54,760
and look at yourself
in that water,

899
00:43:54,800 --> 00:43:56,760
in the candlelight.

900
00:43:56,800 --> 00:43:59,200
Sorry, baby, it's
bigger than both of us.

901
00:43:59,230 --> 00:44:00,500
Kind of a goofball, huh?

902
00:44:00,530 --> 00:44:02,430
Stop it.

903
00:44:02,460 --> 00:44:03,530
You're seriously
bothered?

904
00:44:03,560 --> 00:44:06,960
Just say, "Clay, I need
you to go."

905
00:44:07,000 --> 00:44:09,360
See, this is it.
This is the kind of stuff.

906
00:44:09,400 --> 00:44:11,200
This is why we were
never meant to be.

907
00:44:13,260 --> 00:44:14,460
What are you talking about?

908
00:44:14,500 --> 00:44:16,130
"Never meant to be"?

909
00:44:16,160 --> 00:44:18,230
Does he know he's got
toothpaste on his mouth?

910
00:44:18,260 --> 00:44:20,660
Does he have any idea
how sad and pathetic

911
00:44:20,700 --> 00:44:22,530
this all is?
Clay, I need you to go!

912
00:44:22,560 --> 00:44:24,560
Clay?

913
00:44:25,930 --> 00:44:27,230
Did you say "Clay"?

914
00:44:28,300 --> 00:44:30,330
As in high school Clay?

915
00:44:30,360 --> 00:44:32,130
Is he here?

916
00:44:33,160 --> 00:44:35,700
Allison?

917
00:44:35,730 --> 00:44:37,300
Hey, Allison!

918
00:44:37,330 --> 00:44:39,400
Allison!

919
00:45:34,200 --> 00:45:36,260
(screaming):
Mommy!

920
00:45:36,300 --> 00:45:38,330
Is he in here?
I don't see him, no.

921
00:45:38,360 --> 00:45:39,900
Then where is he, Allison?

922
00:45:39,930 --> 00:45:41,560
I don't know.
I don't see him, either.

923
00:45:41,600 --> 00:45:43,000
You expect me
to believe that?

924
00:45:43,030 --> 00:45:45,000
BRIDGETTE (screaming):
Mommy!

925
00:45:51,760 --> 00:45:54,100
Hello?

926
00:45:54,130 --> 00:45:55,160
Hey, you still coming over?

927
00:45:55,200 --> 00:45:56,230
How'd the drink thing go?

928
00:45:56,260 --> 00:45:58,500
They just left.
It went great.

929
00:45:58,530 --> 00:46:00,530
It went really great.

930
00:46:00,560 --> 00:46:03,360
But I need to talk
to you about something.

931
00:46:03,400 --> 00:46:05,200
Anything.
What's going on?

932
00:46:06,800 --> 00:46:08,660
Hang on a second, honey,
I'm getting another call.

933
00:46:12,860 --> 00:46:15,700
Baby, whatever it is,
it's gonna have to hold.

934
00:46:15,730 --> 00:46:17,530
I just got a call.

935
00:46:17,560 --> 00:46:19,130
Somebody hit a mansion
in Bear Park.

936
00:46:19,160 --> 00:46:20,530
I don't have all
the details yet,

937
00:46:20,560 --> 00:46:23,830
but, uh, looks like I'm gonna
have to run out there.

938
00:46:27,930 --> 00:46:29,900
Hello?

939
00:46:31,260 --> 00:46:32,900
Oh, yes, I understand.

940
00:46:32,930 --> 00:46:34,900
He's right here.

941
00:46:36,430 --> 00:46:38,400
Manuel?

942
00:46:38,430 --> 00:46:40,800
What are you doing?

943
00:46:40,830 --> 00:46:43,830
There's been another one
of those house things.

944
00:46:43,860 --> 00:46:45,860
Okay, I know.

945
00:46:47,260 --> 00:46:48,660
The light is on, right?

946
00:46:48,700 --> 00:46:50,160
You turned
on the lamp?

947
00:46:50,200 --> 00:46:52,060
The lamp is on?
What are you talking about?

948
00:46:52,100 --> 00:46:53,600
Yes, the light is on.
They're on the phone.

949
00:46:53,630 --> 00:46:56,160
Shh, don't panic. Just tell them
I'll call them back.

950
00:46:56,200 --> 00:46:58,660
What are you talking about
you'll "call them back"?

951
00:46:58,700 --> 00:46:59,960
Lilly...

952
00:47:00,000 --> 00:47:01,860
listen to me.

953
00:47:01,900 --> 00:47:04,530
Don't be alarmed...

954
00:47:04,560 --> 00:47:06,360
but I can't see a damn thing.

955
00:47:08,000 --> 00:47:10,300
(crying)
Shh, Bridgette.

956
00:47:10,330 --> 00:47:13,130
(phone ringing)
Sweetie, it was
just a bad dream.

957
00:47:13,160 --> 00:47:15,600
Sweetie, stop. You're
gonna make yourself sick.

958
00:47:17,060 --> 00:47:19,600
It's Scanlon.

959
00:47:19,630 --> 00:47:20,860
Hello?
Come here.

960
00:47:20,900 --> 00:47:22,900
SCANLON (on phone):
Allison, it happened again.

961
00:47:24,400 --> 00:47:26,030
They got the man of the house.

962
00:47:26,060 --> 00:47:27,330
He has a golf club.

963
00:47:27,360 --> 00:47:29,200
The Mom...

964
00:47:29,230 --> 00:47:30,360
In the hall, yeah.

965
00:47:30,400 --> 00:47:32,860
What about the baby?

966
00:47:32,900 --> 00:47:34,900
Did they get the baby?

967
00:47:34,930 --> 00:47:37,400
Yeah, they got the baby, too.

968
00:47:37,430 --> 00:47:39,150
How'd you know?

969
00:47:39,160 --> 00:47:39,160
5

970
00:47:43,110 --> 00:47:44,610
Go to sleep, Joe.

971
00:47:44,650 --> 00:47:46,810
I can't go to sleep.

972
00:47:48,650 --> 00:47:50,650
He's not here.

973
00:47:51,650 --> 00:47:52,810
You don't know that.

974
00:47:54,310 --> 00:47:56,210
I don't see him.
I don't see him anywhere.

975
00:47:56,250 --> 00:47:57,510
I would tell you
if I did.

976
00:47:57,550 --> 00:47:59,450
But you're not
even looking.

977
00:48:01,480 --> 00:48:03,950
I don't see him.

978
00:48:03,980 --> 00:48:06,110
I swear.
Right.

979
00:48:06,150 --> 00:48:08,350
Uh-huh.
What, you don't
believe me?

980
00:48:08,380 --> 00:48:10,880
Allison, the man has
apparently been here

981
00:48:10,910 --> 00:48:12,280
for two whole days.

982
00:48:12,310 --> 00:48:13,650
Now, either you forgot

983
00:48:13,680 --> 00:48:15,610
to mention it or he
can choose when it is

984
00:48:15,650 --> 00:48:17,650
that you see him, and neither
of those two scenarios

985
00:48:17,680 --> 00:48:19,810
makes me particularly
comfortable.

986
00:48:19,850 --> 00:48:21,710
You know, you can
really be an ass.

987
00:48:21,750 --> 00:48:22,850
I didn't do this, Allison.

988
00:48:22,880 --> 00:48:24,310
I'm going to go sleep
in the girls' room.

989
00:48:24,350 --> 00:48:26,950
Go.
Holler if you see a ghost.

990
00:48:26,980 --> 00:48:28,710
Yeah, if you see a ghost,
remember:

991
00:48:28,750 --> 00:48:30,710
you're a married woman.

992
00:48:33,510 --> 00:48:36,150
Hey, "Allibaster."

993
00:48:36,180 --> 00:48:38,110
Your guy's got quite
the temper, huh?

994
00:48:38,150 --> 00:48:39,650
You think he has a temper?

995
00:48:39,680 --> 00:48:41,280
Shh, down, girl.

996
00:48:41,310 --> 00:48:44,480
How dare you--
camp out in my house?!

997
00:48:44,510 --> 00:48:46,480
Toy with my family,
toy with me,

998
00:48:46,510 --> 00:48:48,480
someone you claim to care about?

999
00:48:48,510 --> 00:48:49,650
I hate you.

1000
00:48:49,680 --> 00:48:51,710
No, you don't.
Yes,

1001
00:48:51,750 --> 00:48:54,150
I do and I need you
to leave my house.

1002
00:48:54,180 --> 00:48:56,380
Funny how
things work out.

1003
00:48:56,410 --> 00:48:58,180
You know, when we were in
school, I thought you were

1004
00:48:58,210 --> 00:48:59,710
the smartest thing
on two legs.

1005
00:48:59,750 --> 00:49:02,210
When we were in school,
I thought you were smug.

1006
00:49:02,250 --> 00:49:05,450
And vain and selfish
and nice to look at

1007
00:49:05,480 --> 00:49:06,950
and maybe, deep down,
had a heart.

1008
00:49:06,980 --> 00:49:08,480
I guess I was wrong
about the heart.

1009
00:49:08,510 --> 00:49:11,350
You know, he's mistaken
about you in there.

1010
00:49:11,380 --> 00:49:13,280
Pissed off becomes you.

1011
00:49:13,280 --> 00:49:14,710
Leave my house!

1012
00:49:14,750 --> 00:49:16,750
Don't you think I
would, if I could?

1013
00:49:16,780 --> 00:49:19,750
Well, maybe you just
have to try harder.

1014
00:49:19,780 --> 00:49:22,210
Come on, you can do it.

1015
00:49:22,250 --> 00:49:24,410
Find a light
and walk into it.

1016
00:49:24,450 --> 00:49:26,250
You think it's just
a coincidence I ended up here,

1017
00:49:26,280 --> 00:49:27,780
out of all the places
in all the world?

1018
00:49:27,810 --> 00:49:29,410
Your house?

1019
00:49:29,450 --> 00:49:32,150
You think it's an
accident you can see me?

1020
00:49:32,150 --> 00:49:35,450
Hear me? I don't.

1021
00:49:35,480 --> 00:49:38,050
I've been to a lot of places,
I've seen a lot of things.

1022
00:49:38,080 --> 00:49:40,380
I don't believe in coincidence.

1023
00:49:40,410 --> 00:49:41,910
I'm here for a reason...

1024
00:49:41,950 --> 00:49:44,580
like it or not, baby.

1025
00:49:44,610 --> 00:49:46,610
I think that
reason is you.

1026
00:49:48,110 --> 00:49:50,750
Mommy, I got scared and I
thought I heard voices.

1027
00:49:52,250 --> 00:49:54,950
It's just me, sweetie,
talking to myself.

1028
00:49:54,980 --> 00:49:56,810
Did you have a bad dream?

1029
00:49:56,850 --> 00:49:59,910
Uh... kind of.

1030
00:49:59,910 --> 00:50:02,880
Do you want to come in my
bed and sleep with me?

1031
00:50:02,910 --> 00:50:04,650
That might make it all better.

1032
00:50:06,980 --> 00:50:08,580
If you don't mind.

1033
00:50:08,610 --> 00:50:10,010
Okay, just this once.

1034
00:50:10,050 --> 00:50:11,910
As long as we don't
make a habit out of it.

1035
00:50:11,950 --> 00:50:14,010
(chuckles):
Okay.

1036
00:50:17,080 --> 00:50:19,680
(beeping)
MAN:
Mr. Devalos.

1037
00:50:19,710 --> 00:50:22,280
I'm going to shine a very bright
light into your eyes.

1038
00:50:22,310 --> 00:50:23,550
I need you to tell me
if you see something.

1039
00:50:23,580 --> 00:50:25,550
Anything.

1040
00:50:25,580 --> 00:50:27,110
DEVALOS:
Uh, yeah.

1041
00:50:27,150 --> 00:50:30,080
It's very blurry, but I can see.

1042
00:50:30,110 --> 00:50:32,980
I see you and I see the room.

1043
00:50:33,010 --> 00:50:34,580
And I can see you, Lilly.

1044
00:50:34,610 --> 00:50:37,650
My best guess is
that we're looking
at a severe case

1045
00:50:37,680 --> 00:50:39,580
of diabetic retinopathy.

1046
00:50:39,610 --> 00:50:41,150
Blood sugar's
off the charts.

1047
00:50:41,180 --> 00:50:43,080
You're lucky you
can see at all.

